# git-worktree-management-patterns — History

## v2.7.0 (2026-05-10)

**Changed by:** Multi-repo CI sweep 2026-05-10 (Odysseus easy-sweep agent self-corrected wrong-path edit)
**Verification:** unverified (template is hypothetical until next sub-agent dispatch validates it)

### What changed

- Bumped version 2.6.0 → 2.7.0; updated date to 2026-05-10
- Added trigger (18) to description and "When to Use" bullet: writing dispatch prompts for `Agent(isolation="worktree")` sub-agents that will call Read/Edit on a repo where the user might have a dirty main checkout — explicit worktree path discipline must be in the prompt
- Added new Failed Attempts row: sub-agent dispatched with `Agent(isolation="worktree")` used bare repo paths in Read/Edit calls instead of the worktree subpath; agent self-corrected via `git checkout` in user's checkout, then re-applied edits in the worktree
- Added new Results & Parameters subsection: "Sub-agent dispatch prompt template — worktree path discipline" with a copy-paste-ready prompt block
- Updated Overview Outcome line to reference v2.7.0 changes

### Why

Sub-agents dispatched via `Agent(isolation="worktree")` can bypass worktree isolation if they use bare repo paths in Read/Edit. The Read/Edit tools accept any path; the harness does not enforce that paths stay inside the agent's worktree. The Odysseus easy-sweep agent on 2026-05-10 hit this exact failure mode mid-task: it issued Read/Edit calls against `/home/mvillmow/Projects/Odysseus/...` instead of the worktree subpath at `/home/mvillmow/Projects/Odysseus/.claude/worktrees/agent-<id>/`. The agent self-detected, ran `git checkout` on the affected files in the user's main checkout to revert, and re-applied its edits inside the actual worktree. PR #278 still shipped successfully, but mid-task recovery is more expensive than prevention. Adding the prompt template as a documented dispatch artifact makes prevention cheap and repeatable.

