## v2.3.0 (2026-04-06)

**Changed by:** Session — stale /tmp/mnemosyne-skill-* blocker pattern for parallel /learn sub-agents
**Verification:** verified-local (observed in Odysseus e2e walkthrough session 2026-04-06)

### What changed
- Bumped version from 2.2.0 to 2.3.0, updated date to 2026-04-06
- Extended `description` / When to Use list with item (12): "cleaning stale /tmp/mnemosyne-skill-* worktree directories before parallel /learn sub-agents"
- Added new "When to Use" bullet for the pre-spawn cleanup pattern
- Added new Failed Attempts row: Stale `/tmp/mnemosyne-skill-*` path blocking parallel `/learn` sub-agents
- Added new Safety Net interaction row for `rm -rf /tmp/mnemosyne-skill-*` inside sub-agents
- Added new Results & Parameters section "Stale /tmp/mnemosyne-skill-* cleanup before parallel /learn sub-agents" with orchestrator pre-cleanup snippet and timestamp-suffix alternative

### Why
During a `/hephaestus:learn` session that spawned 3 parallel sub-agents to amend ProjectMnemosyne
skills, 2 of the 3 agents immediately failed with a worktree creation error because
`/tmp/mnemosyne-skill-<name>` directories from prior `/learn` invocations still existed on disk.
The shared clone's worktree registry still referenced these paths, so `git worktree add` refused
to create new worktrees at the same paths.

Root cause: `/learn` sub-agents create worktrees at predictable paths. If a prior session's
cleanup failed (due to agent timeout, Safety Net blocking `rm -rf`, or session interrupt),
the directory persists and the next invocation hits `fatal: already exists`. The Safety Net
also blocks `rm -rf /tmp/mnemosyne-skill-*` when run inside a sub-agent, so the fix must be
run by the orchestrator (main conversation) before spawning sub-agents.

### Previous version (v2.2.0) snapshot

Key v2.2.0 guidance before this amendment:

```markdown
